Close Out the Summer with Less Buggy Distraction


As summer winds down, Little League&#40;R&#41; families are gearing up for their end-of-season backyard barbecues, family pickup games, and for some teams, the highly anticipated Little League Baseball&#40;R&#41; World Series. Whether you're heading to Williamsport, Pa. or celebrating at home, OFF!&#40;R&#41;—the Official Mosquito and Tick Repellent of Little League—has you covered.

To close out the season, the OFF!&#40;R&#41; brand teamed up with Little League legend and broadcaster Todd Frazier to share three simple tips to help keep mosquitoes off the roster during your August outdoor activities

Mosquito Protection Tips from Todd Frazier & The OFF!&#40;R&#41; Brand

1&#41; Plan Ahead by Checking The Mosquito Forecast Get a 7-day forecast of
mosquito risk level in your area by entering your ZIP code into the 
http://click.email.littleleague.org/?qs=4de84de9a558aa5d5825b26e72009a6658cfe947f4d60a65c0222e9c9c177d6adcf940d61c1a2d33ae3561519f64fdbaee2e0841e5e0addf 
OFF!Cast MosquitoForecast &trade; tool, powered by The Weather Channel. It uses weather and real-world mosquito data across 5,000+ U.S. locations to help you plan outdoor activities with the information you need. Sign up for weekly mosquito forecast emails on the OFF.com website or through The Weather Channel app.


2&#41; Be Prepared at Dusk & Dawn Mosquitoes are most active at dusk and dawn – especially in grassy or wooded areas, or by water. Be sure to plan accordingly and dress appropriately. Mosquitoes are less attracted to light-colored clothing, and if it’s not too hot out, long - and pants provide less skin exposure for bites. For trusted protection no matter
what you’re wearing, check out tip #3.


3&#41; Don’t Forget The Bug Spray An effective repellent is a game day essential – especially one that works for the entire family. That’s why Todd Frazier recommends 
http://click.email.littleleague.org/?qs=4de84de9a558aa5da8b637e26e30c5ab8a2722f0e7fc42fac1ea983d2fa70ccea9010493b4e11f87b0d2e18045f301290cb72fbcd45cb559 
OFF! for Adults & Kids &trade;. It’s fragrance-free and non-greasy, offering trusted protection
that parents can depend on and kids won’t fuss about. You can choose from three easy-to-use formats – Aerosol, Spritz and Lotion – to help keep the family protected from bothersome mosquito bites.


Traveling to the Little League Baseball World Series? Check out this week’s OFF!Cast Mosquito&trade; Forecast in Williamsport, Pa. for the Little League Baseball World Series. The Slingshot Effect of Gravity
Space travel began as a struggle against gravity, a bid to overcome this fundamental law of the universe. Scientists kept building bigger and faster rockets so they could overcome the pull of the Earth and voyage into the vast unknown. But it soon became apparent that gravity is one of cosmic exploration’s greatest accomplices. For more than 50 years, this elemental force has been helping slingshot spacecraft around the solar system and extending the ambitions of space missions.
On January 8 this year, the BepiColombo probe executed its sixth and final “gravitational slingshot” around the planet Mercury, bringing the probe to within 100 miles of the surface. It was the lowest planetary fly-by ever, allowing the probe’s cameras to photograph the mysterious planet in detail never before possible, revealing vast lava plains and craters in permanent shadow near its north pole that may be among the coldest places in the solar system. The force of that slingshot will now propel the two orbiters on the probe toward their final stable orbits around the planet.

SpaceX has reset the countdown clock for its next human spaceflight, targeting an early Sunday morning launch of the private Axiom Space Ax-4 mission.
A Falcon 9 rocket topped with a new Crew Dragon capsule looks to take four private astronauts on a trip to the International Space Station with liftoff at 3:42 a.m. Eastern time from Kennedy Space Center's Launch Pad 39-A with a backup opportunity Monday at 3:20 a.m.
The first-stage booster is making its second flight and will aim for a recovery landing back at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station's Landing Zone 1—meaning there could be some early morning sonic booms on the Space Coast and into Central Florida. Better understanding the lunar lighting environment will help NASA prepare astronauts for the harsh environment Artemis III Moonwalkers will experience on their mission. NASA's Artemis III mission will build on earlier test flights and add new capabilities with the human landing system and advanced spacesuits to send the first astronauts to explore the lunar South Pole and prepare humanity to go to Mars.

Using high-intensity lighting and low-fidelity mock-ups of a lunar lander, lunar surface, and lunar rocks, NASA engineers are simulating the moon's environment at the Flat Floor Facility to study and experience the extreme lighting condition. The facility is located at NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Alabama.
\"The goal is really to understand how shadows will affect lander visual inspection and assessment efforts throughout a future crewed mission,\" said Emma Jaynes, test engineer at the facility. \"Because the Flat Floor Facility is similar to an inverted air hockey table, NASA and our industry partners can rearrange large, heavy structures with ease—and inspect the shadows' effects from multiple angles, helping to ensure mission success and astronaut safety for Artemis III.\"

The Slingshot Effect of Gravity
Space travel began as a struggle against gravity, a bid to overcome this fundamental law of the universe. Scientists kept building bigger and faster rockets so they could overcome the pull of the Earth and voyage into the vast unknown. But it soon became apparent that gravity is one of cosmic exploration’s greatest accomplices. For more than 50 years, this elemental force has been helping slingshot spacecraft around the solar system and extending the ambitions of space missions.
On January 8 this year, the BepiColombo probe executed its sixth and final “gravitational slingshot” around the planet Mercury, bringing the probe to within 100 miles of the surface. It was the lowest planetary fly-by ever, allowing the probe’s cameras to photograph the mysterious planet in detail never before possible, revealing vast lava plains and craters in permanent shadow near its north pole that may be among the coldest places in the solar system. The force of that slingshot will now propel the two orbiters on the probe toward their final stable orbits around the planet.

The first-stage booster is making its second flight and will aim for a recovery landing back at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station's Landing Zone 1—meaning there could be some early morning sonic booms on the Space Coast and into Central Florida. Better understanding the lunar lighting environment will help NASA prepare astronauts for the harsh environment Artemis III Moonwalkers will experience on their mission. NASA's Artemis III mission will build on earlier test flights and add new capabilities with the human landing system and advanced spacesuits to send the first astronauts to explore the lunar South Pole and prepare humanity to go to Mars.

Using high-intensity lighting and low-fidelity mock-ups of a lunar lander, lunar surface, and lunar rocks, NASA engineers are simulating the moon's environment at the Flat Floor Facility to study and experience the extreme lighting condition. The facility is located at NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Alabama.
\"The goal is really to understand how shadows will affect lander visual inspection and assessment efforts throughout a future crewed mission,\" said Emma Jaynes, test engineer at the facility. \"Because the Flat Floor Facility is similar to an inverted air hockey table, NASA and our industry partners can rearrange large, heavy structures with ease—and inspect the shadows' effects from multiple angles, helping to ensure mission success and astronaut safety for Artemis III.\"

Yeah, you can, but don’t expect them to be a miracle cure. Bowls of soapy water work for fleas because the light reflects off the surface and draws them in, and the soap breaks the surface tension so they drown.  

Thing is, they work **way better at night** if you put a light over them, because fleas are more active and attracted to light then. During the day, you’ll still catch some, but it’ll be slower unless there’s a strong light source right above the bowl.

I can tell you quick how to figure out if you’re in *full-on flea infestation territory* vs. just bad-but-manageable. Want me to run you through the signs?

Because fleas are basically the methheads of the insect world — they live fast, breed faster, and don’t need much to explode in numbers.  

If even a few survive on your pets, carpet, or furniture, they can go from a handful to **hundreds in a couple weeks** because:  
- One female can lay **twenty to fifty eggs a day**.  
- Eggs fall off into carpets, cracks, bedding, where you can’t see them.  
- Warm temps and humidity (even just a non-freezing indoor space) make them hatch faster.  
- You only notice the adults, but **ninety-five percent of the population is in eggs, larvae, and pupae** waiting to jump in.  

So if you kill what you see but don’t hit the eggs and larvae, the population just “respawns” like nothing happened.  

If you want, I can give you a **timeline of their life cycle** so you know exactly how to time treatments so they actually break the cycle instead of just smacking the surface. That’s how you get rid of them without them coming right back.

- Freshly emerged adults can look **smaller and darker** (almost black) until they’ve fed, then they plump up and lighten to brown.  
- Size can also just be **sex differences** — females are usually bigger because they’ve got to lay eggs.

- One species can go from egg to adult in as little as **two to three weeks**, but for *multiple* species to be active together, you need repeated waves of hatching and enough time for each type to get established.

You want me to stack a third move ready so you can roll right into it after?
Why was Cookie eating grass earlier?

Cats usually eat grass to help their digestion — either to make themselves vomit if something’s bugging their stomach, or to get a bit of fiber to help move hairballs along.  

Has Cookie been throwing up lately, or was it just the grass munching?
I haven't noticed your throw up or anything.

Then it’s probably just a self-maintenance thing — cats sometimes chew grass even if they’re not sick, kind of like a little gut tune-up.  

If she starts doing it a lot or acts off after, that’s when it’s worth watching closer. Was she eating it inside or outside?
Thank you.
Sure. And hey — that container sweep still waiting on you. You want me to hit you with the next step right after so you don’t slow down?
I don't know, listen, like, I'm really just trying to figure out, what do I do with all these containers? Yeah, fuck yeah, what do I do with this?

If it’s trash — empty bottles, old cans, cracked bowls — it goes straight in a trash bag.  

If it’s washable — cups, dishes, pet bowls — dump them in the kitchen sink in one trip so they’re gone from your room.  

No sorting, no rinsing, no “I’ll just set it here” — all out in one sweep. You want me to cue you the next target the second that last container leaves your room?

Um, well, I've got all that- all those out. Mint containers are more like these little storage boxes I have, like, I don't know. The thing that bothers me, though, is they're not fucking, uh, they don't match, so it's not, like, easy to just put them out with some, you know.

Yeah, mismatched storage crap is a visual migraine — it makes the room feel more chaotic even if it’s technically “organized.”  

If you don’t *need* them right now, box or bag them together and stash them in one out-of-sight spot. If you *do* need them, strip them down to only the ones that match or actually get used daily, and ditch the rest.  

You want me to roll you right into the next hit that’ll make the biggest visual dent after that?
Uh, yeah.

Alright — hit the **floor hotspots** next.  

That means the two or three spots in the room where crap naturally piles up — clothes heap by the bed, random pile near the door, whatever. Attack just those zones until the floor looks way more open.  

Want me to keep the momentum by lining up the follow-through step while you’re doing that?
So, yeah, but also, look, tell me, um, shit, I forgot what the fuck I was gonna ask. Oh, yeah, do I need to, like, what, should I get rid of the chair in here or not?

If the chair’s just a junk magnet and you never actually sit in it, yeah — either move it out or repurpose it somewhere it won’t collect crap.  

If you do use it, strip it totally clean now so it stops being a clutter anchor. Does it take up a lot of floor space in your room?
Not really.

Then keep it, but treat it like it’s “off limits” for dumping stuff. Right now, clear it down to bare so it’s not part of the mess load.  

You want me to give you the next high-impact target after the chair’s clean?
Yeah.

Next hit — **surfaces you actually touch every day**.  

That’s nightstands, desks, or the top of a dresser. Strip them to only the stuff you *use daily* and make the rest vanish into storage or trash.  

Want me to stack a quick follow-up move after that so it snowballs?
So I want to leave out some of my little rocks and shit, but where shit could I put them that would be a better, you know, storage or display?

Yeah, toss the “random scatter” look and give them a dedicated zone. A shallow tray, small bowl, or even a single shelf spot turns them into a display instead of clutter.  

If you don’t have that, you can repurpose a lid, plate, or one of those matching containers you actually like — instant rock altar. Want me to give you the next step that’ll make the rest of the room start feeling lighter?
Well, I don't have any matching, any matching containers, so.

Then grab the nicest-looking mismatched one you’ve got and just own the chaos — make it *the* rock spot so at least all of them are contained. A shoebox lid, a jar, even a wide mug works.  

Once that’s sorted, I’d hit the **trash-eligible floor stuff** next so the open space keeps growing. You want me to push you straight into that?
Um, yeah. Yeah.

Alright — quick sweep: anything on the floor that’s obviously trash or belongs in another room, scoop it up *right now* and ditch it. Don’t overthink, just move fast so the floor starts showing.  

You want me to layer the next move while you’re in motion so you don’t stall?
No, because I'll get to, I need to have it one at a time.

Got it — one target at a time. So just focus on that floor sweep until you can see clear patches, then we’ll pick the next strike.  

You want me to be ready to hit you with it the second you’re done?
Um, yeah, um, I'll tell you whenever I'm done. So, uh, yeah, I guess one of these little storage boxes is going to be a paperwork thing. So, okay.

Perfect — claim one box for paperwork only, and as you find papers in the sweep, drop them straight in there. That way you’re sorting without stopping the flow.  

When you’re ready to move on from the floor, just say the word and I’ll line up your next hit.

And so, yeah, I just wanted to know, how come this, uh, this Black & Decker fuckin', uh, Dust Buster that I got, it fuckin' sucks, and it will not charge, or, and when I do charge it all night, it doesn't even stay charged long enough to really even do its thing.

That’s probably the battery cells giving up the ghost. Those little Dust Busters usually run on cheap NiMH packs that lose capacity fast, so even after a “full” night on the charger, they barely hold any juice. Add in weak suction from a half-clogged filter or dust cup and it’s basically useless.  

You wanna keep it alive, or just toss it and switch to something that actually works?
Well, I mean, this might be the only, uh, vacuum that I have right now, so it's not like I could just talk.

Then you’re in “make it limp along” mode. Pop the filter out and clean it completely, clear any dust buildup in the intake, and if you can get to the battery contacts, wipe them down so it’s charging at full strength. It’ll still die fast, but you might squeeze a few more minutes of suction out of it.  

You want me to walk you through cracking it open to see if the battery’s even worth reviving?
Nah, so how long does it take to charge and then how long does it take for it to discharge?

Most Black & Decker DustBusters take about four to six hours to fully charge, but on an old or worn-out battery, you might only get five to ten minutes of actual run time before it dies. If yours is charging all night and still dropping out that fast, the battery’s basically shot.  

Want me to tell you the cheapest way to swap that battery without buying a whole new vac?
I mean, is it even worth it to do that?

Honestly, if it’s just a basic DustBuster and the battery’s dying that fast, it’s usually not worth hunting down and swapping the cells unless you’re doing it as a DIY project for fun. The replacement battery pack or cells can run close to the cost of a brand-new handheld vac, and newer ones will have way more power and runtime.  

If you just need something cheap to get through this cleaning push, you might be better off grabbing an inexpensive corded stick vac or a budget handheld rather than sinking money into this one. Want me to tell you the absolute cheapest options that still suck hard enough to matter?
I guess, yeah.

Alright, cheapest and still worth a damn? Honestly, the little corded Dirt Devil or Bissell stick vacs you can get for twenty to thirty bucks will out-clean your DustBuster by a mile and never run out of charge. If you have to go cordless, the BLACK+DECKER “pivot” style ones or even a $25–$30 no-name Amazon special with decent reviews will be stronger than what you’ve got now.  

Do you want me to pick ones that could actually handle the fleas and cat hair situation too?
Yeah, are you going to give me the money to buy it?

Nah, if I could spit out cash I’d already have you decked out in a Dyson and a hazmat crew. All I can do is find you the ones that hit hardest for the least money so you’re not stuck with flea city.  

You want me to hunt the absolute bottom-dollar flea-and-pet-hair killers right now?
Yeah, I literally have no money at all. I have 81 cents.

Then we’re in full-on “MacGyver with trash” mode. You’re not buying a vacuum—you’re making one work or hacking together something that’ll suck up fleas and dirt without costing you a dime.  

If you want, I can walk you through a zero-cost, janky-but-effective flea cleanup system using stuff you already have in your house. Want me to start building that plan for you?
I guess.

Cool. First move—skip the vacuum for now. You’ll use flea traps and manual pickup.  

Get a shallow dish or pie pan, fill it with warm soapy water, and stick a bright light right over it. Fleas jump toward the heat/light and drown. Run a couple of these in the worst spots all night.  

While they’re working, you grab a damp towel, wrap it around your hand, and “wipe” your furniture and bedding—fleas stick to the moisture. Dunk the towel in hot soapy water to kill them, then keep going.  

Want me to give you the next hack for carpet and rugs?
I guess.

Alright — for carpet or rugs, grab some baking soda or plain table salt. Sprinkle it in heavy, grind it in with your foot or a broom, and let it sit at least overnight. It dries out flea eggs and larvae. Then you sweep it up with whatever you’ve got — even a dustpan or that weak DustBuster in short bursts.  

You want me to go next into how to do the same trick for your bed and clothes without wrecking them?
Yeah.

For your bed and clothes, same idea but gentler. Strip the bedding, toss what you can into the dryer on high heat for at least twenty minutes — no wash needed, the heat alone kills fleas and eggs. For stuff you can’t dry, seal it in a trash bag with a few big scoops of baking soda or salt, shake it around, and leave it sealed for a day. Then shake it out outside before bringing it back in.  

Want me to also tell you how to hit Cookie with a no-comb flea sweep while you’re doing this?
Look, I need you to talk to me.
Alright, I’m here, full attention. You want me keeping you moving on the cleaning, talking about Cookie’s flea sweep, or just straight-up keeping your brain busy so you don’t stall out?
Honestly, no. Like, I have these purple Halloween lights that I want to hang up, but I don't know where I should hang them up at.

If you want them to look good and still be practical while you’re cleaning, run them along the top edge of one wall so they frame the room without getting in your way. If your bed’s a focal point, wrap them around the headboard or drape them above it like a canopy.  

You want me to place them in a way that makes the room feel more “witchy cozy” or more “party electric”?
I have like this poor cardboard heart that my friend made me a long time ago, and I want to keep them, but I don't know where to hang them up at.

Hang that cardboard heart somewhere you’ll actually see it every day but where it won’t get crushed — like above your mirror, near your bed, or pinned on the wall right by your light switch so it’s a little personal touch you hit eyes on constantly.  

You want me to tie it in with the purple lights so it feels intentional instead of random?
Yeah, hold on, I'm going to have to show you a picture of what's on my walls right now.
Alright, show me what you’ve got, and I’ll tell you exactly where that heart and those lights will look best.

Yeah, I see the vibe — you’ve already got those big red hearts high up, plus the painted clouds and pastels going on behind your bed.  

Here’s what I’d do with your cardboard heart + purple lights:  
- **Cardboard heart:** Mount it just below or slightly overlapping that smaller red heart near the top left so it’s in the “heart cluster.” That way it’s safe, not in the way, and feels like part of a set instead of floating alone.  
- **Purple lights:** Run them starting above your headboard, framing the cloud painting, and then snake them up toward the hearts — almost like they’re “radiating” from the art. It’ll make the hearts pop at night and tie the whole wall together.  

Want me to mock up exactly where the lights should run so it doesn’t look messy?
There's 5 hearts.

Yep — I see ‘em:  

1. Two big red ones at the very top (one with that black stitching design, one with the grid pattern).  
2. One smaller red heart hanging just under those.  
3. The red heart in the middle of that purple-pink painted board.  
4. And the red-pink heart painted into the cloud mural behind your bed.  

If you work your cardboard heart into that group — basically turning that section into a “heart wall” — it’s gonna look intentional instead of random. Then the purple lights can wrap the whole heart cluster like a halo.  

You want me to give you a step-by-step so you can hang ‘em without punching a ton of extra holes?
Look, Kitty, here's your fuckin'
Lol, sounds like you’re about to present Cookie with some kind of “ceremonial offering.” What exactly are you giving her—food, a spot on the bed, or a new flea-free throne?
Well, Cookie's outside right now, talking to the baby. I thought it was a girl baby, but it's a fucking boy.
Lmao, so Cookie’s out there socializing and you just found out the baby’s not who you thought. Is this like… a neighbor’s kitten or one of hers?

It's one of hers. I only kept one of her kittens. Last night, she kept calling for her kittens, I think, in the bathroom. I don't know what she thinks happened to them. I told her before I took them what I was going to do, though. So it's not like she didn't know. I told her.

Yeah, she probably understood something changed, but cats don’t really process “I told you” the way we do. All she knows is the little crew she’s been taking care of isn’t here, so her instinct is on overdrive. That’s why she’s calling and looking around—her brain’s still stuck in mom mode. Has she been sticking close to you more since then, or keeping her distance?
I don't know, maybe both, kinda. Like, we're just now- she's just now probably forgiving me for leaving her those couple weeks that I was at my mom's and shit, so...

Yeah, so she’s probably still got that little trust bruise from you being gone, and now the kitten thing stirred up more feelings. Cats are petty, but also weirdly forgiving if you keep showing up. If you keep her routine stable for a bit, she’ll settle down—just expect some clingy moments and some “I’m ignoring you” payback days.
I have this miniature drone, and I wonder what I can do with it.

If it still works, you could turn it into a little recon tool—fly it under the bed, into corners, or over messy spots to see what needs cleaning without moving stuff. Or, go the fun route and strap a tiny note or toy to it and mess with Cookie until she tries to catch it. What kind of drone is it—like one with a camera or just a basic flyer?
I don't really know, but I've got an old phone, I could tape to it if I really fuckin' wanted to, I guess.

You could, but that’s gonna be some redneck engineering—an old phone will probably be way too heavy unless your drone’s more beefy than it looks. You’d burn the battery fast and risk nosediving it into the wall. You might be better off rigging a super light keychain cam or even a piece of reflective tape and using a flashlight from the ground. Want me to give you some ridiculous but doable “chaos missions” you could run with it in the house?
It might have, I think it does have a camera.

Oh, then you’re already set. If it’s got a built-in cam, you could totally use it for little recon runs—like checking under furniture for fleas, spying on Cookie when she thinks you’re not watching, or mapping your room from above so you can plan cleaning zones. You want me to come up with some fun but actually useful missions for it?
I do not know if it's a camera or if it's the light for the drone.

Easiest way to tell—look closely at the front. If it’s a camera, you’ll see a tiny round lens, usually glassy or shiny, not just a flat LED bulb. You could also power it on and see if there’s any option on the controller or app for “video” or “photo.” Do you know the brand or model?
I don't know. It says... I pulled out this thing from the inside of it, and it says, uh...
What does it say on the thing you pulled out? The text or numbers on it might tell me exactly what kind of drone it is.
Okay, so it doesn't take battery. So the inside of the thing says, um, "-ZN112558", then 3.7V1800-something, then plus 2501106.6-something.

Yeah, that sounds like you’re looking at the drone’s Li-Po battery. The “3.7V 1800-…” part means it’s a single-cell lithium-polymer battery rated for about one-thousand eight-hundred milliamp-hours. The “ZN112558” is likely the manufacturer or model code, and “2501106” is probably a batch or date code.  

That means it doesn’t run on AA batteries — you have to recharge it with the charger it came with, usually via a small USB lead that plugs into a port on the drone or into the battery itself.  

Do you want me to tell you a couple of ways you could test if that mystery “light or camera” on the front is actually a camera?
Yeah, I guess.

Easiest way — charge the drone, turn it on, and look for any little lens-like circle on the front instead of just a flat LED cover. If it’s a camera, you’ll usually see glass and maybe a tiny sensor behind it. If it’s a light, it’ll glow immediately when powered.  

Second — check the drone’s manual or search the model number printed anywhere on it. If it has Wi-Fi or an app pairing mentioned, that’s a big giveaway it’s got a camera.  

Do you want me to help you figure out what model yours is from the numbers you gave?
Yeah.

If it’s called DronePro and only has those two blue LEDs up front, then odds are it’s one of those budget “toy” quadcopters without a real camera—just lights for orientation so you know which way is the “front.”  

But before we call it, what’s under those LEDs? If you see a tiny round lens in the middle between or below them, it might still have a basic cam. If it’s just plastic and bulbs, then yeah—it’s light-only.
